            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the tipping calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tipping calculator helps you quickly decide how much to tip
                and how to split the bill fairly with friends or family. It
                supports any currency, custom tip percentages, optional tax, and
                rounding so you can match local customs and your budget.
              </p>

              <h3>Tip formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Tip</strong> = Bill × (Tip % ÷ 100)</p>
                <p><strong>Total</strong> = Bill + Tip</p>
                <p><strong>Per‑person tip</strong> = Tip ÷ Number of people</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Per‑person total</strong> = Total ÷ Number of people
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Pre‑tax vs post‑tax tipping</h3>
              <p>
                Many etiquette guides recommend calculating the tip on the
                pre‑tax amount, because tax is not part of the service. Others
                simply tip on the final total because it is easier. The
                calculator lets you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Enter the bill amount (with or without tax).</li>
                <li>
                  Optionally enter the tax rate to see:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Estimated tax amount.</li>
                    <li>Tip if you calculate on the pre‑tax subtotal.</li>
                    <li>Tip if you calculate on the post‑tax total.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Typical tipping percentages by situation</h2>
              <p>
                These are general guidelines. Always check local customs and
                your bill (service may already be included).
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Restaurants (table service)</strong>: 15–20% in the
                  US/Canada; 5–10% or rounding up in much of Europe if service
                  is not included.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bars &amp; cafés</strong>: Round up or leave small
                  change; in North America, $1–2 per drink or 15–20% of the tab.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Taxis &amp; ride‑shares</strong>: 10–15% in countries
                  where tipping is common; round up elsewhere.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hotels</strong>: A few units of local currency per bag
                  for porters; a modest daily amount for housekeeping in tipping
                  cultures.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hairdressers &amp; salons</strong>: 10–20% in North
                  America; smaller or no tip where service charges are included.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>International tipping etiquette (quick overview)</h2>
              <p><strong>United States &amp; Canada</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Tipping is a major part of income for many service workers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Restaurants: 15–20% is standard, more for exceptional service.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Leaving no tip is usually seen as a strong negative signal.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p><strong>Italy and much of Western Europe</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Service (servizio) may already be included in the bill; check
                  the receipt.
                </li>
                <li>A cover charge (coperto) is common and is not a tip.</li>
                <li>
                  Locals often round up or leave a small extra amount (5–10%)
                  for good service.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                <strong>Countries where tipping is rare or discouraged</strong>
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  In some countries, tipping is not expected and can even be
                  refused.
                </li>
                <li>
                  When in doubt, ask a local or check a recent travel guide.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is it better to tip a fixed amount or a percentage?</h3>
              <p>
                Percentages scale with the size of the bill and are standard in
                restaurants and taxis. For very small bills, a fixed amount (for
                example, rounding up to the nearest convenient number) can be
                more practical.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I handle service charges already on the bill?</h3>
              <p>
                If the bill lists a service charge, that usually replaces the
                tip. You can still leave a small extra amount for exceptional
                service, but it is not required. In the calculator, you can
